<span id="iii.vii.xix"></span>

<span id="iii.vii.xix-p1"></span> <span class="c11"><span
id="iii.vii.xix-p1.1"></span>Chapter XVIII.—</span>*The Works of
Philo* <span id="fr_419"></span>[420](#fn_419.md) *that have come down to
us.*

<span id="iii.vii.xix-p3"></span>1. <span class="c13"><span
id="iii.vii.xix-p3.1"></span>Copious</span> in language, comprehensive
in thought, sublime and elevated in his views of divine Scripture, Philo
has produced manifold and various expositions of the sacred books. On
the one hand, he expounds in order the events recorded in Genesis in the
books to which he gives the title *Allegories of the Sacred Laws*; <span
id="fr_420"></span>[421](#fn_420.md) on the other hand, he makes successive
divisions of the chapters in the Scriptures which are the subject of
investigation, and gives objections and solutions, in the books which he
quite suitably calls *Questions and Answers on Genesis and
Exodus*. <span id="fr_421"></span>[422](#fn_421.md)

<span id="iii.vii.xix-p6"></span>2. There are, besides these, treatises
expressly worked out by him on certain subjects, such as the two books
*On Agriculture*, <span id="fr_422"></span>[423](#fn_422.md) and the same
number *On Drunken*<span id="page_120">p. 120</span> <span
id="iii.vii.xix-Page_120"></span>*ness*; <span
id="fr_423"></span>[424](#fn_423.md) and some others distinguished by
different titles corresponding to the contents of each; for instance,
*Concerning the things which the Sober Mind desires and
execrates,* <span id="fr_424"></span>[425](#fn_424.md) *On the Confusion of
Tongues,* <span id="fr_425"></span>[426](#fn_425.md) *On Flight and
Discovery,* <span id="fr_426"></span>[427](#fn_426.md) *On Assembly for the
sake of Instruction,* <span id="fr_427"></span>[428](#fn_427.md) *On the
question, ‘Who is heir to things divine?’* or *On the division of things
into equal and unequal,* <span id="fr_428"></span>[429](#fn_428.md) and
still further the work *On the three Virtues which with others have been
described by Moses.* <span id="fr_429"></span>[430](#fn_429.md)

<span id="iii.vii.xix-p16"></span>3. In addition to these is the work
*On those whose Names have been changed and why they have been
changed,* <span id="fr_430"></span>[431](#fn_430.md) in which he says that
he had written also two books *On Covenants.* <span
id="fr_431"></span>[432](#fn_431.md)

<span id="iii.vii.xix-p20"></span>4. And there is also a work of his *On
Emigration,* <span id="fr_432"></span>[433](#fn_432.md) and one *On the
life of a Wise Man made perfect in Righteousness,* or *On unwritten
Laws;* <span id="fr_433"></span>[434](#fn_433.md) and still further the
work *On Giants* or *On the Immutability of God,* <span
id="fr_434"></span>[435](#fn_434.md) and a first, second, third, fourth and
fifth book *On the proposition, that Dreams according to Moses are sent
by God.* <span id="fr_435"></span>[436](#fn_435.md) These are the books on
Genesis that have come down to us.

<span id="iii.vii.xix-p25"></span>5. But on Exodus we are acquainted
with the first, second, third, fourth and fifth books of *Questions and
Answers;* <span id="fr_436"></span>[437](#fn_436.md) also with that *On the
Tabernacle,* <span id="fr_437"></span>[438](#fn_437.md) and that *On the
Ten Commandments,* <span id="fr_438"></span>[439](#fn_438.md) and the four
books <span id="page_121">p. 121</span> <span
id="iii.vii.xix-Page_121"></span>*On the laws which refer especially to
the principal divisions of the ten Commandments,* <span
id="fr_439"></span>[440](#fn_439.md) and another *On animals intended for
sacrifice* and *On the kinds of sacrifice,* <span
id="fr_440"></span>[441](#fn_440.md) and another *On the rewards fixed in
the law for the good, and on the punishments and curses fixed for the
wicked.* <span id="fr_441"></span>[442](#fn_441.md)

<span id="iii.vii.xix-p32"></span>6. In addition to all these there are
extant also some single-volumed works of his; as for instance, the work
*On Providence,* <span id="fr_442"></span>[443](#fn_442.md) and the book
composed by him *On the Jews,* <span id="fr_443"></span>[444](#fn_443.md)
and *The Statesman;* <span id="fr_444"></span>[445](#fn_444.md) and still
further, *Alexander,* or *On the possession of reason by the irrational
animals.* <span id="fr_445"></span>[446](#fn_445.md) Besides these there is
a work *On the proposition that every wicked man is a slave,* to which
is subjoined the work *On the proposition that every goad man is
free.* <span id="fr_446"></span>[447](#fn_446.md)

<span id="iii.vii.xix-p38"></span>7. After these was composed by him the
work *On the contemplative life,* or *On suppliants,* <span
id="fr_447"></span>[448](#fn_447.md) from which we have drawn the facts
concerning the life of the apostolic men; and still further, the
*Interpretation of the Hebrew names in the law and in the prophets* are
said to be the result of his industry. <span
id="fr_448"></span>[449](#fn_448.md)

<span id="iii.vii.xix-p41"></span>8. And he is said to have read in the
presence of the whole Roman Senate during the reign of Claudius <span
id="fr_449"></span>[450](#fn_449.md) the work which he had written, when he
came to Rome under Caius, concerning Caius’ hatred of the gods, and to
which, with ironical reference to its character, he had given the title
*On the Virtues.* <span id="fr_450"></span>[451](#fn_450.md) And his
discourses were so much admired as to be deemed worthy of a place in the
libraries.

<span id="iii.vii.xix-p44"></span>9. At this time, while Paul was
completing his journey “from Jerusalem and round about unto
Illyricum,” <span id="fr_451"></span>[452](#fn_451.md) Claudius drove the
Jews out of Rome; and Aquila and Priscilla, leaving Rome with the other
Jews, came to Asia, and there abode with the apostle Paul, who was
confirming the churches of that region whose <span id="page_122">p.
122</span> <span id="iii.vii.xix-Page_122"></span>foundations he had
newly laid. The sacred book of the Acts informs us also of these
things. <span id="fr_452"></span>[453](#fn_452.md)

